The material dates from 1966-2005, and was created and collected by Brian Furness in connection with his work as a community leader in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Washington, D.C. bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Brian R. Furness was a long-time resident of and community activist for the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Washington, D.C. Most notably, Furness was a member of the Capitol Hill Restoration Society (CHRS) from 1972 until his relocation to New Orleans, Louisiana in 2005. He served CHRS in various roles, including as its President (1998-2001), First Vice President, Second Vice President, and Secretary. Furness served as Chair of several CHRS committees, including the Community Development Committee. He was also CHRS's representative to the Eastern Market Community Advisory Committee (EMCAC), and served as Chair of EMCAC's Management and Operations Subcommittee. He was President of the Bryan School Neighborhood Association.

Furness worked for the Foreign Service Reserve Corps of the U.S. State Department from 1966-89, spending much of that period abroad in Brazil, Italy, and Venezuela. He received his Bachelor of Arts in Political Science from Washington University in St. Louis, and did additional work in Economics at the Foreign Service Institute and The George Washington University.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains correspondence, minutes, reports, legal documents, financial documents, newsletters, clippings, promotional materials, photographs, and other materials. The material dates from 1966-2005, and was created and collected by Brian Furness in connection with his work as a community leader in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Washington, D.C. The papers reflect Furness' involvement with a number of civic organizations, most notably the Capitol Hill Restoration Society. The Capitol Hill Restoration Society (CHRS) is the largest civic association on Capitol Hill. Its mission is to protect the residential character of the area and to support Eastern Market and other business districts. Eastern Market was built in 1873 and remains the last nineteenth century market in continuous operation in Washington, D.C.

The papers largely document Furness' work in support of zoning regulations to preserve the architectural integrity and residential character of the neighborhood through his involvement with CHRS, Eastern Market Community Action Committee, Bryan School Neighborhood Association and other groups. The papers deal with community efforts to ensure that new residential development was compatible with existing structures and neighborhood uses. Three series in particular, Boys Town, Bryan School, and Kentucky Courts, deal specifically with housing issues. Other issues addressed in the collection include business development, traffic control, crime, and historic preservation.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into seven series: Capitol Hill Restoration Society, Eastern Market, Boys Town, Bryan School, Station Place, Kentucky Courts, Other issues in the Capitol Hill neighborhood.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, minutes, reports, legal documents, financial documents, newsletters, clippings, promotional materials, photographs, and other materials related to the organization and structure of the Capitol Hill Restoration Society. The materials date from 1978-2005. The Capitol Hill Restoration Society (CHRS) is the largest civic association on Capitol Hill. Its mission is to protect the residential character of the area and to support Eastern Market and other business districts. Whenever possible, Furness' original organization of these documents has been preserved. In cases where no organization could be detected, the documents have been arranged chronologically in "general files." The general files contain materials relating both to the administration of the CHRS (e.g., meeting minutes, agenda, internal correspondence) and the many community issues with which the CHRS was involved. Note materials related to specific issues, sorted by topic, are contained in the remaining series of the collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, minutes, legal documents, financial documents, reports, clippings, and other materials related to Eastern Market. The materials date from 1966-2005. Eastern Market was built in 1873 and remains the last nineteenth century market in continuous operation in Washington, D.C. It includes a traditional indoor market, a farmers market, flea market, and arts and crafts market. This series contains documents created and collected by the Eastern Market Community Task Force (EMCTF), a community group organized and chaired by the Capitol Hill Restoration Society to examine and devise solutions to management issues at Eastern Market. EMCTF was dissolved with the passage of legislation in 1998. The series also includes documents created and collected by Eastern Market Community Advisory Committee (EMCAC), an organization created by Eastern Market Act legislation. Brian Furness served as CHRS's representative to EMCAC and as chair of its Management and Operations Subcommittee.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, legal documents, clippings, minutes, notes, flyers, newsletters related to a proposal by the nonprofit organization Girls and Boys Town to build a facility for at risk youth in Capitol Hill. The material dates from 2000-03. The series includes materials created and collected by Southeast Citizens for Smart Development (SCSD), a community organization that led the successful efforts to block the development of the Boys Town facility.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, legal documents, clippings, notes, newsletters and other materials related to the redevelopment of the Bryan School, a decommissioned public elementary school located at 1357 Independence Avenue, SE. The materials date from 1992-2003. They include materials created and collected by the Bryan School Neighborhood Association (BSNA), a community group organized to pilot neighborhood efforts to use and redevelop the school building. Brian Furness served as President of BSNA.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, legal documents, clippings, notes, and other materials related to the development of the area adjacent to the Union Station rail yard on 2nd Street between F and H Streets NE. The materials date from 1989-2001. The materials focus largely on traffic and transportation issues associated with this project.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains legal documents, correspondence, clippings, reports, notes and other materials related to the redevelopment of the Kentucky Courts Dwellings, a public housing project. The materials date from 1996-2001. They include materials created and collected by the Kentucky Courts Neighborhood Task Force (KCNTF), a community group which promoted the demolition of the old Kentucky Courts family dwellings and the construction of mixed-income neighborhood-compatible housing.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, legal documents, clippings, minutes, notes, flyers, newsletters related to various other issues affecting the Capitol Hill neighborhood. The materials date from 1984-2005. The materials cover a variety of community concerns including the sale and development of government-owned properties, traffic and transportation issues, historic preservation, and the creation of business improvement districts.
